{"parse":{"title":"let","pageid":7017,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"let\"}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{abbrev|mul|-}} {{der|mul|en|'''Le'''sing-A'''t'''ui}}.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|lett||archaic}}\n* {{alt|en|lettest||2nd person singular simple present and simple past; archaic}}\n* {{alt|en|letteth||3rd person singular simple present; archaic}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/lɛt/}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-let.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-let.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛt|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|en|Lett}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{der+|en|enm|leten}}, {{m|enm|læten}}, from {{der|en|ang|lǣtan||to allow, let go, bequeath, leave, rent}}, from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*lātan}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*lētaną||to leave behind, allow}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*leh₁d-||to be tired, leave}}.\n\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|lat}}, {{m|sco|lete||to let, leave}}, {{cog|yol|leth||let}}, {{cog|frr|leet}}, {{m|frr|let}}, {{m|frr|lätje||to let}}, {{cog|bar|låssn||to let}}, {{cog|nl|-}}, {{cog|nds|laten||to let, leave}}, {{cog|de|lassen}}, {{m|de|laßen||to let, leave, allow}}, {{cog|lb|loossen||to let, leave}}, {{cog|yi|לאָזן||to let}}, {{cog|da|lade||to let, allow, leave}}, {{cog|fo|-}}, {{cog|is|láta||to let}}, {{cog|nb|la||to let, leave}}, {{cog|nn|la}}, {{m|nn|lata}}, {{m|nn|late||let, allow}}, {{cog|sv|låta||to let, allow, leave}}, {{cog|got|𐌻𐌴𐍄𐌰𐌽||to let}}, {{cog|sq|lë||to allow, let, leave}} and partially related to [[French]] {{m|fr|laisser||to let}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb|~s|~ting|~,leet<l:obsolete>|+,~ten<l:obsolete>}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[allow]] to, not to prevent {{qualifier|+ infinitive, but usually without {{m|en|to}}}}.\n#: {{ux|en|After he knocked for hours, I decided to '''let''' him come in.}}\n#* {{RQ:KJV|Exodus|8|28|passage=Pharaoh said, I will '''let''' you go.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Hamlet|act=IV|scene=vi|passage=If your name be Horatio, as I am '''let''' to know it is{{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1971|author=w:Ursula K. Le Guin|title=w:The Tombs of Atuan\n|passage=He could not be '''let'''<!--sic--> die of thirst there alone in the dark.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-21|author=w:Oliver Burkeman| volume=189| issue=2| page=27| magazine=w:The Guardian Weekly| title=[http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2013/may/10/conscious-computing-twitter-facebook-google The tao of tech]| passage=The dirty secret of the internet is that all this distraction and interruption is immensely profitable. Web companies like to boast about [&hellip;], or offering services that '''let''' you \"stay up to date with what your friends are doing\",{{...}}and so on. But the real way to build a successful online business is to be better than your rivals at undermining people's control of their own attention.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To allow to be or do without interference; to not disturb or meddle with; to [[leave alone]].\n#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' me be!}}\n#* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|book=II|canto=VI|stanza=16|passage=Yet neither spinnes nor cardes, ne cares nor frets, / But to her mother Nature all her care she '''lets'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To allow the release of (a fluid).\n#: {{ux|en|The physicians '''let''' about a pint of his blood, but to no avail.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|chiefly|British}} To allow possession of (a property etc.) in exchange for [[rent]].\n#: {{ux|en|I decided to '''let''' the farmhouse to a couple while I was working abroad.}}\n#* {{RQ:Austen Pride and Prejudice|volume=I|chapter=I|pages=1–2|passage=“My dear Mr. Bennet,” said his lady to him one day, “have you heard that Netherfield Park is '''let''' at last?”<br>Mr. Bennet replied that he had not.<br>“But it is,” returned she; “for Mrs. Long has just been here, and she told me all about it.”}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|text=Trailers for sale or rent, rooms to '''let''', fifty cents.|year=1965|author=Roger Miller|title=King Of The Road}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give, grant, or assign, as a work, privilege, or contract; often with ''out''.\n#: {{ux|en|to '''let''' the building of a bridge; &emsp;to '''let''' out the lathing and the plastering}}\n# {{lb|en|auxiliary|transitive}} {{non-gloss|Used to introduce a first or third person imperative verb construction.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Let''''s put on a show!}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' us have a moment of silence.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' me just give you the phone number.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' ''P'' be the point where ''AB'' and ''OX'' intersect.}}\n#: {{ux|en|\"'''Let''' there be no doubt: I saw you boyfriend with another girl\" \"'''Let''' him. I don't care anymore\".}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete|_|except with [[know]] or [[be]]}} To [[cause]] {{qualifier|+ bare infinitive}}.\n#: {{ux|en|Can you '''let''' me know what time you'll be arriving?}}\n#* {{RQ:Mlry MrtDrthr|6.4|2|IV|iv|passage=Soo within a whyle kynge Pellinore cam with a grete hoost and salewed the peple and the kyng and ther was grete ioye made on euery syde. Thenne the kyng '''lete''' serche how moche people of his party ther was slayne. And ther were founde but lytel past two honderd men slayne and viij knyȝtes of the table round in their pauelions.|t=So after a while King Pellinore came with a great host and saluted the people and the king, and there was great joy on every side. Then the king '''let''' search how many people of his faction were slain. And there were found only a little more than two hundred men slain, and eight knights of the Table Round in their pavilions.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1818|author=w:John Keats|title=To—\n|passage=Time's sea hath been five years at its slow ebb, / Long hours have to and fro '''let''' creep the sand{{nb...}}.}}\n#* {{RQ:Thoreau Walden|chapter=The Ponds|page=212|passage=What right had the unclean and stupid farmer, whose farm abutted on this sky water, whose shores he has ruthlessly laid bare, to give his name to it? ... Rather '''let''' it be named from the fishes that swim in it, the wild fowl or quadrupeds which frequent it, the wild flowers which grow by its shores, or some wild man or child the thread of whose history is interwoven with its own...}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* The use of “let” to introduce an imperative may sometimes be confused with its use, ''as its own imperative'', in the sense of “to allow”. For example, the sentence “'''Let''' me go to the store.” could either be a second-person imperative of “let” (addressing someone who might prevent the speaker from going to the store) or a first-person singular imperative of “go” (not implying any such preventer).\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|to allow}} {{l|en|allow}}, {{l|en|permit}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|en|bloodlet|lettable|letter|lettor|relet|unlet\n|buy-to-let,buy to let\n|don't let the bedbugs bite\n|don't let the door hit you on the way out\n|forlet\n|if it's yellow let it mellow|let a sleeping dog lie|let things alone|let things be\n|inlet\n|let alone\n|let a thousand flowers bloom\n|let be\n|let blood\n|let bygones be bygones\n|let down\n|let drive\n|let fluffy off the chain|let crazy stick its dick in you|let into|let one's nuts hang|let this cup pass from me|let through|ship and let ship\n|let fly\n|let George do it|let someone hold\n|let go|let me tell you|let us see\n|let her rip|let that sink in\n|let he who is without sin cast the first stone\n|let him that is without sin cast the first stone\n|let him who is without sin cast the first stone\n|let in|let them eat cake\n|let in on\n|let it all hang out\n|let it alone\n|let it be\n|let it be known\n|let it snow\n|let know\n|let lie\n|let loose\n|let me count the ways\n|let me see\n|let nature take her course\n|let Nature take its course\n|let nature take its course\n|let-off\n|let off\n|let off steam\n|let on\n|let one go\n|let one loose\n|let one off\n|let one rip\n|let one's guard down\n|let one's hair down\n|let one's short back and sides down\n|let out\n|let past\n|let rip\n|let's\n|let sleeping dogs lie\n|let slide\n|let slip\n|let someone have it\n|let someone loose\n|let something ride\n|let something slip\n|let the buyer beware\n|let the cat out\n|let the cat out of the bag\n|let the chips fall where they may\n|let the cobbler stick to his last\n|let the devil out\n|let the dice fall where they may\n|let the dog see the rabbit\n|let the door hit you where the good Lord split you\n|let the good times roll\n|let the grass grow round one's feet\n|let the grass grow under one's feet\n|let the matter drop\n|let them have it\n|let the perfect be the enemy of the good\n|let there be light\n|let the sleeping dogs lie\n|let up\n|let us\n|let us count the ways\n|let us go\n|let well alone\n|let well enough alone\n|live-and-let-live\n|live and let live\n|offlet\n|outlet\n|re-let\n|sublet\n|take the cash and let the credit go\n|to let\n|underlet\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|allow}}\n* Albanian: {{t|sq|lë}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|سَمَحَ}}, {{t|ar|دَعَّ}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|خلَى|tr=ḵella}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|թողնել}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|alas}}, {{t|rup|las}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|dexar}}\n* Bangi: {{t|bni|tika}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|пуска́ць|impf}}, {{t|be|пусці́ць|pf}} {{q|let go}}, {{t|be|дазваля́ць|impf}}, {{t|be|дазво́ліць|pf}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|lezel}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|позволявам}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|permetre}}, {{t+|ca|deixar}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|讓|tr=ràng}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|nechat}}, {{t+|cs|dovolit|pf}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|tillade}}, {{t+|da|lade}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|laten}}, {{t+|nl|toestaan}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|lasi}}, {{t|eo|permesi}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|laskma}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|antaa}}, {{t+|fi|sallia}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|laisser}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|lassâ}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|deixar}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ნების დართვა}}, {{t|ka|გაშვება}}\n* German: {{t+|de|lassen}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|επιτρέπω}}, {{t+|el|αφήνω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἐάω}}, {{t|grc|ἀφίημι}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Mbya Guarani: {{t|gun|eja}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|הִנִּיחַ|tr=hinníaẖ}}\n* Hmong:\n*: White Hmong: {{t-needed|mww}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|hagy}}, {{t+|hu|enged}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|leyfa}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|lasar}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|lassar}}\n* Istriot: {{t|ist|lassà}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|lasciare}}, {{t+|it|permettere}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|させる|tr=...saseru|alt=...させる}} {{qualifier|causative form}}\n* Khmer: {{t|km|អោយ}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|허락하다}}\n* Ladin: {{t|lld|lascer}}\n* Lao: {{t-needed|lo}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|sinō}}, {{t+|la|patior}}, {{t|la|permittō}}, {{t+|la|sustineō}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|ļaut}}, {{t|lv|laist}}\n* Lingala: {{t|ln|tika}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t+|lt|leisti}}\n* Livonian: {{t|liv|laskõ}}\n* Lombard: {{t+|lmo|lassà}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|дозволи}}\n* Neapolitan: {{t|nap|lassà}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+|no|la}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|permetre}}, {{t+|oc|daissar}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|lǣtan}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|گذاشتن|tr=gozâštan}}, {{t+|fa|اجازه دادن|tr=ejâze dâdan}}\n* Piedmontese: {{t|pms|lassé}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|pozwalać|impf}}, {{t+|pl|pozwolić|pf}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|deixar}}, {{t+|pt|permitir}}, {{t+|pt|ir}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|sagii}}, {{t|qu|hagii}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|lăsa}}\n* Romansh: {{t|rm|laschar}}, {{t|rm|lascher}}, {{t|rm|schar}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|пуска́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|пусти́ть|pf}} {{q|let go}}, {{t+|ru|позволя́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|позво́лить|pf}}\n* Sardinian: {{t|sc|lassai}}, {{t|sc|lassare}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|leig le}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+|sh|dopustiti}}, {{t+|sh|dati}}\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|пустити|pf}}, {{t|sh|дозволити|pf}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|pustiti|pf}}, {{t+|sh|dozvoliti|pf}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|lassari}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|nechať}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|pustiti|pf}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{t|dsb|daś}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|permitir}}, {{t+|es|dejar}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|låta}}\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|hayaan}}, {{t|tl|pabayaan}}\n* Telugu: {{t|te|ఇవ్వు}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|ให้}}, {{t+|th|ปล่อย}}\n* Tibetan: {{t-needed|bo}}\n* Tocharian B: {{t|txb|kälm-}}, {{t|txb|tärk-}}\n* Turkish:\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|براقمق|tr=bırakmak}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|пуска́ти|impf}}, {{t|uk|пусти́ти|pf}} {{q|let go}}, {{t|uk|дозволя́ти|impf}}, {{t|uk|дозво́лити|pf}}\n* Venetan: {{t+|vec|lasar}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|trở|lit=to give}}, {{t+|vi|để}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|leyî}}, {{t+|wa|laire}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|gadael}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|לאָזן}}\n* Zhuang: {{t-needed|za}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|leave}}\n* German: {{t+|de|lassen}}, {{t+|de|zurücklassen}}, {{t+|de|verlassen}}\n* Turkish:\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|براقمق|tr=bırakmak}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|allow the release of (a fluid)}}\n* German: {{t+|de|ablassen}}, {{t|de|herauslaufen lassen}}\n* Hebrew: {{t|he|הִקִּיז|tr=hiqqíz}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|put up for rent}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|давам под наем}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|出租|tr=chūzū}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|pronajmout|pf}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|verhuren}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[antaa]] [[vuokra]]lle}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|louer}}\n* German: {{t+|de|vermieten}}, {{t+|de|überlassen}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|bérel}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|affittare}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|貸す|tr=かす, kasu}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|임대하다}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|izīrēt}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|nuomoti}}, {{t|lt|išnuomoti}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|leie ut}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|wynajmować}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|alugar}}\n* Russian: {{t|ru|[[сдава́ть]] в [[аренда|аре́нду]]|impf}}, {{t|ru|[[сдать]] в [[аренда|аре́нду]]|pf}}, {{t|ru|[[сдава́ть]] [[внаём]]|impf}}, {{t|ru|[[сдать]] [[внаём]]|pf}}, {{t+|ru|сдава́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|сдать|pf}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|thoir seachad air mhàl}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|posuditi}}, {{t+|sh|iznajmiti}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|alquilar}}, {{t+|es|arrendar}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|louwer}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|introducing an imperative}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|хай}}, {{t|be|няхай}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|нека}}, {{t+|bg|да}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|ať}}, {{t+|cs|nechť}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|lade}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|הָבָה|tr=háva}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|niech}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|să|alt=(hai) să}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|пусть}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|хай}}, {{t|uk|нехай}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# The allowing of possession of a property etc. in exchange for [[rent]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Charles Dickens|year=1854|text=Then he says “You would call it a Good '''Let''', Madam?”<br>“O certainly a Good Let sir.”|page=317|title=Christmas Stories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g5IPAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA317&lpg=PA317&dq=You+would+call+it+a+Good+Let,+Madam?%E2%80%9D&source=bl&ots=9BRzev-gor&sig=ACfU3U0YQUKYQyiIkPQgMUw4tCOygSrkUQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjNtralhq3pAhUKknIEHUC3CjsQ6AEwAHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=You%20would%20call%20it%20a%20Good%20Let%2C%20Madam%3F%E2%80%9D&f=false}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|holiday let}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{der+|en|enm|letten||to hinder, delay}}, from {{der|en|ang|lettan||to hinder, delay”; literally, “to make late}}, from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*lattjan}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*latjaną}}. Akin to {{cog|ang|latian||to delay}}, {{cog|nl|letten}}, {{cog|ang|læt||late}}. More at [[late]], [[delay]].\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb|+|+|+|~}}\n\n# {{lb|en|archaic}} To [[hinder]], [[prevent]], [[impede]], [[hamper]], [[cumber]]; to [[obstruct]] {{gl|someone or something}}.\n#* {{RQ:King James Version|2 Thessalonians|2|7|passage=He who now '''letteth''' will '''let''', until he be taken out of the way.}}\n#* {{RQ:Tennyson Idylls|page=152|passage=Sir King, mine ancient wound is hardly whole, / And '''lets''' me from the saddle; {{...}}}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[prevent]] someone from doing something; also to [[prevent]] something from happening.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1485|author=w:Thomas Malory|title={{w|Le Morte Darthur}} Book XXI, Chapter ii, [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/c/cme/MaloryWks2/1:23.2?rgn=div2;view=fulltext leaf 421r]|text=''& there was syr Mordred redy awaytynge vpon his londage to '''lette''' his owne fader to lāde vp the lande that he was kyng ouer.''<br>\"And there was Sir Mordred ready awaiting upon his landing, to '''let''' his own father to land upon the land that he was king over.\"}}\n#* {{RQ:Tyndale NT|Acts|8|passage=And as they went on their waye, they cam unto a certayne water, and the gelded man sayde: Se here is water, what shall '''lett''' me to be baptised?}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[tarry]] or [[delay]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1826|section=The History of Sir Eger, Sir Grahame, And Sir Gray-Steel|title=Early Metrical Tales; Including the History of Sir Egeir, Sir Gryme, and Sir Gray-Steill|location=Edinburgh|page=7|passage=And for that strake I would not '''let''', / Another upon him soon I set, {{...}}}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|obsolete|or|legal}} An [[obstacle]] or [[hindrance]].\n#: {{ux|en|without '''let''' or hindrance}}\n#* {{RQ:Latimer Sermons|volume=II|sermon=XXV|chapter=Preached on the Twenty First Sunday after Trinity|date=12 June 1552|page=541|passage=[E]ver conſider vvhether our doings be to the '''let''' of our ſalvation or not.}}\n#* {{RQ:Ovid Golding Metamorphosis|book=3|lines=60–61|passage=And Cadmus saw his campanie make tarience in that sort / He marveld what should be their '''let''', and went to seeke them out.}}\n#* {{RQ:Montaigne Florio Essayes|chapter=16|book=II|passage=''Paulus Emilius'' going to the glorious expedition of ''Macedon'', advertised the people of ''Rome'' during his absence not to speake of his actions: ''For the licence of judgements is an especiall '''let''' in great affaires.''}}\n# {{lb|en|tennis}} The [[hindrance]] caused by the [[net]] during [[serve]], only if the ball falls legally.\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|without let or hindrance}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|hindrance}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|obstáculo|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+|sh|prepreka}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|hindrance caused by the net during serve at tennis}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|filet|m}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Netzball|m}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|tukurua}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===References===\n* [http://www.dsl.ac.uk/entry/dost/let_v The Dictionary of the Scots Language]\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=elt|ELT|ETL|LTE|TEL|TLE|Tel.|elt|tel}}\n\n{{cln|en|irregular past participles|irregular simple past forms|irregular verbs}}\n\n==Ahtna==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom or related to {{m|aht|łet||smoke}}.\n\n====Root====\n{{head|aht|root}}\n\n# a [[smudge]] or [[smokey]] [[fire]] [[burn]]s\n# to (cause to) burn to [[ash]]es\n\n=====Stem set=====\n{{aht-stem-set-header}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|dur|let|let|let|let}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|mom|liit|let|liił|liit}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|conc|let|let|let|let}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|aht\n|dedlet<t:it is smoldering>\n}}\n\n====References====\n* {{Kari|page=278}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Root====\n{{head|aht|root}}\n\n# to [[wobble]]\n\n=====Stem set=====\n{{aht-stem-set-header}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|mom|let|let|let|let}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|cust|liit|liit|liit|liit}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|aht\n|keghalet<t:it is wobbling>\n}}\n\n====References====\n* {{Kari|page=277}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Root====\n{{head|aht|root}}\n\n# to [[melt]]\n\n=====Stem set=====\n{{aht-stem-set-header}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|mom|laat|let|leł|laat}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row2|prog|{{l|aht|leł}}|—|—|—}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|aht\n|cʼghaleł<t:it is melting>\n}}\n\n====References====\n* {{Kari|page=277}}\n\n==Champenois==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|roa-cha|leuil|leil|q=Rémois}}\n* {{alter|roa-cha|leu|q=Langrois}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|roa-cha|fro|lit}}, from {{inh|roa-cha|la|lectus}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|roa-cha|/lɛ/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|roa-cha|noun|g=m|plural|lets}}\n\n# {{lb|roa-cha|Troyen|Langrois}} [[bed]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:roa-cha:Daunay}}\n* {{R:roa-cha:Baudouin}}\n\n==Czech==\n{{wp|cs:}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{cs-IPA}}\n* {{audio|cs|Cs-let.ogg}}\n* {{homophones|cs|led}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|cs|sla-pro|*letъ}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{cs-noun|m-in}}\n\n# [[flight]] {{gl|the act of [[flying]]}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{cs-ndecl|m}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n{{col|cs\n|letět\n|letový\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|cs|noun form|g=n}}\n\n# {{infl of|cs|léto||gen|p}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:cs:PSJC}}\n* {{R:cs:SSJC}}\n* {{R:cs:IJP}}\n\n==Danish==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|da|gmq-oda|læt}}, from {{inh|da|non|léttr}}, from {{der|da|gem-pro|*linhtaz}}. Cognate with {{cog|sv|lätt}}, {{cog|is|léttur}}, {{cog|en|light}}, {{cog|nl|licht}} and {{cog|de|leicht}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|[ˈlɛd̥]}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{da-adj||lette}}\n\n# [[light]] {{gl|not heavy}}\n# [[easy]]\n# [[slight]]\n# [[mild]]\n\n=====Inflection=====\n{{da-infl-adj|lett|est}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|easy}} {{l|da|nem}}, {{l|da|enkel}}\n\n====Adverb====\n{{head|da|adverb}}\n\n# [[lightly]]\n# [[easily]]\n# [[slightly]]\n# [[mildly]]\n\n====References====\n* {{R:DDO|let,2}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nAbbreviation of {{m|da|letmælk}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|[ˈlɛd̥]}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{da-noun|en|stem=lett}}\n\n# [[low-fat]] [[milk]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{da-decl|en|stem=lett}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:DDO|let,1}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|[ˈlɛd̥]}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|da|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|da|lette||imp}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|[ˈleˀd̥]}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|da|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|da|le||past|participle}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-let.ogg}}\n* {{rhymes|nl|ɛt|s=1}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|nl|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nl|letten||bare-ten-verb}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{l|nl|tel}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|fr|:bor|en:let}}\n{{bor+|fr|en|let}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA|lète}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Xenophôn-let.wav}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-LoquaxFR-let.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-WikiLucas00-let.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Lyon>>)}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{fr-intj}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|tennis}} {{n-g|indicates a let on service}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n==Friulian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|fur|la|lēctus}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|legō}}.\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|fur|verb form}}\n\n# {{past participle of|fur|lei|nocat=1|t=read}}\n\n==Gothic==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{got-rom|head=lēt}}\n\n# {{romanization of|got|𐌻𐌴𐍄}}\n\n==Irish==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|ga|led}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ga|/lʲɛt̪ˠ/}}\n\n===Contraction===\n{{head|ga|contraction|triggers {{ga-mut-link|l}}}}\n\n# {{lb|ga|Munster}} {{contraction of|ga|le|do|lit=with your {{g|s}}}}\n#: {{ux|ga|[[le do thoil|'''let''' thoil]]|please|inline=1}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{ga-preposition contractions}}\n\n==North Frisian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|frr|leet||Föhr-Amrum}}\n* {{alt|frr|lätje||Mooring}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|frr|ofs|lēta}}, from {{inh|frr|gmw-pro|*lātan}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|frr|[lɛt]}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|frr|verb}}\n\n# {{lb|frr|Sylt}} to {{l|en|let}}\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{frr-Sylt-conj-table|inf_2=leten|ppp=leten|pres_2=letst|pres_3=let|past_1=let|past_2=letst}}\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{der+|nb|non|litr||colour}}, related to {{m|non|líta||to see}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{nb-noun-m1}}\n\n# [[color]] / [[colour]]\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|nb|farge}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|nb|hamlet}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|nb|verbf}}\n\n# {{infl of|nb|lete||imp}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nb:OB}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|nn|non|litr||colour}}, from {{inh|nn|gem-pro|*wlitiz}}, {{m|gem-pro|*wlituz}}. Related to {{cog|non|líta||to see}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{nn-fcon|2012}} {{alt|nn|lett}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-m2}}\n\n# [[color]] / [[colour]]\n#: {{syn|nn|farge}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|nn|einleta}}\n* {{l|nn|hamlet}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|nn|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nn|la||pres|tense}}\n# {{infl of|nn|lata||pres}}\n# {{infl of|nn|la||past|tense}}\n# {{infl of|nn|lata||past}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|nn|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nn|leta||imp}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|nn|a=elt|elt|etl|lèt|lét|tel}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|lēt}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|ang|verb form|head=lēt}}\n\n# {{infl of|ang|lǣtan||1//3|s|pret|indc}}\n\n==Serbo-Croatian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|sh|sla-pro|*letъ}}. {{etydate|17th century}}.<ref>{{R:sh:ERHJ|let|547|1}}</ref>\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sh-IPA|lȇt}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sh-noun|lȇt|m-in}}\n\n# [[flight]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{sh-decl-noun\n|lȇt|létovi\n|lȇta|létōvā\n|lȇtu|létovima\n|lȇt|létove\n|lȇte|létovi\n|létu|létovima\n|lȇtom|létovima\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|sh|lèteti}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:sh:HJP|e19iXxA%3D}}\n\n==Slovene==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|sl|sla-pro|*letъ}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sl-IPA|lȅt}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sl-noun|lȅt|m-in}}\n\n# [[flight]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{sl-decl-noun-m|lèt|lét}}\n\n==Tok Pisin==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{der+|tpi|en|leather}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tpi|noun}}\n\n# [[leather]]\n# [[strap]] {{gl|of leather}}\n# [[belt]]"}}